      {
        "id": "parallelization",
        "title": "Parallel Power: Why Transformers Train Faster",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- O(1) sequential ops vs O(n) for RNN\n- O(n²·d) attention complexity\n- GPU utilization\n\nSelf-attention computes all pairwise interactions in one matrix multiply — O(1) sequential steps versus RNN's O(n) sequential steps, enabling massive GPU parallelism at the cost of O(n²) memory.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "transformer_descendants",
        "title": "The Legacy: BERT, GPT, and Beyond",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- encoder-only: BERT\n- decoder-only: GPT\n- encoder-decoder: T5\n\nDecoder-only (GPT) applies causal masks for autoregressive generation; encoder-only (BERT) uses full bidirectional attention for representation learning. This single architectural choice drives the generative vs discriminative split in modern LLMs.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-3",
      "question": "GPT-style models use only the Transformer decoder stack. BERT-style models use only the encoder stack. What is the key difference in their attention masking? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "GPT uses causal masking; BERT uses bidirectional (no masking)",
        "Both use causal masking",
        "BERT uses causal masking; GPT uses none"
      ],
